Single-database Alembic configuration for Flask.

The committed chain starts with `c5e0e7e0560d`, adds the verification-delivery
outbox in `61f2c8e4a9bd`, immutable publication persistence in `13eb10903bd7`,
governed recommendation rule sets in `be7dfc45f976`, Issue #38 engagement and
reminder integrity in `7f3c2a91d8e4`, and canonical subscription node-type
ordering in `4d8b6e1a3f20`. Issue #37 revision/lifecycle evidence follows in
`8b4d2f7a1c90`, and privacy-minimized outbound click analytics are added in
the current head `a64f1b9d2c7e`.

Fresh databases apply the complete chain. A database at the known
`13eb10903bd7` predecessor can upgrade to the governed recommendation schema
when its legacy mutable `recommendation_rules` table is empty. The initial
migration records whether it adopted a fresh database or an older
`db.create_all()` schema. On the legacy path, authentication tables and
identities are bridged, while the immutable publication migration leaves
unknown business-table shapes unchanged. Reset an old disposable database
before upgrade. For a shared database, write and review a dedicated
data-preserving publication bridge instead of stamping or guessing series,
edition, revision, or recommendation-rule lineage.

A database already at the known `61f2c8e4a9bd` predecessor uses the committed
publication bridge: owned mutable competitions become one-series/one-edition
revision snapshots, existing nodes and tags are revision-scoped, and public
visibility is retained. Rows without `created_by_id` are rejected before schema
mutation so an operator can assign a real owner instead of receiving invented
review attribution.

## Recommendation governance revision

The `be7dfc45f976` upgrade follows `13eb10903bd7` and fails closed before
destructive DDL when the legacy mutable `recommendation_rules` table contains
rows. The table, its data, and the `13eb10903bd7` predecessor state remain
available for operator review. Do not stamp the database, guess lineage, discard
those rows, or automatically promote unreviewed mutable rules into active v1.
Before retrying, back up the database and make an explicit, reviewed
data-migration decision.

Downgrading from `be7dfc45f976` to `13eb10903bd7` is a destructive schema
rollback, not a history-preserving governance rollback. It removes governed
rule-set and rule snapshots, drops the recommendation review snapshot columns,
and recreates an empty legacy mutable `recommendation_rules` table. Before
downgrading a shared database that contains governed recommendation data, back
up and export the data and approve an explicit rollback plan.

## Issue #38 engagement and reminder revisions

`7f3c2a91d8e4` follows `be7dfc45f976`. A database still at `13eb10903bd7`
therefore applies the independent recommendation-governance revision first. If
legacy recommendation rules block that step, the database remains at
`13eb10903bd7`; once it reaches `be7dfc45f976`, the Issue #38 preflight owns the
next transition.

The Issue #38 revision does not alter a recorded `legacy_create_all` database.
On its supported `be7dfc45f976` predecessor, it first refuses an upgrade if
`favorites`, `subscriptions`, or `reminders` contains retained rows. The
engagement schema stays unchanged and the database remains at `be7dfc45f976`;
an operator must reset a disposable database or use a separately reviewed
bridge before changing that populated engagement data.

For an empty engagement predecessor, the revision preserves each existing
`reminder_settings` row and creates one missing row for every student. A row
uses the legacy profile's `message_enabled` and `default_remind_days` when a
profile exists, otherwise `true` and `3`; all created rows use the controlled
default node-type order. Because this backfill assigns explicit setting IDs, it
synchronizes PostgreSQL's `reminder_settings.id` sequence afterwards.

The revision adds favorite and subscription uniqueness, the subscription
confirmation timestamp and `0..30` reminder-day check, and reminder snapshot,
logical-key, revision, cancellation, and delivery-attempt fields with the
ordinary-plan uniqueness constraint. It then removes duplicate reminder columns
from `student_profiles`.

Its downgrade to `be7dfc45f976` also refuses retained engagement rows. With no
such rows it restores profile compatibility columns from authoritative
`reminder_settings` rows, refusing the downgrade when any student profile lacks
a setting row, then removes the Issue #38 engagement constraints and columns.
Recommendation-governance data and schema remain intact at that predecessor.

`4d8b6e1a3f20` follows `7f3c2a91d8e4`. It normalizes every persisted
`subscriptions.node_types` value to the controlled order
`registration_deadline`, `submission_deadline`, `competition_start`. It refuses
the upgrade and reports row IDs for malformed JSON, non-list/non-string,
duplicate, or unknown values. Its downgrade is intentionally a no-op: ordering
normalization is lossless because prior request order was never contractual.

## Issue #37 revision and lifecycle evidence

`8b4d2f7a1c90` follows `4d8b6e1a3f20`. It adds source-backed replacement
reasons and lifecycle warning context, plus idempotent competition-event
message dimensions used by approved revision reconciliation. Its downgrade
removes those evidence columns and constraints, so export any retained
lifecycle or schedule-change message evidence before a shared-database
rollback.

`a64f1b9d2c7e` follows `8b4d2f7a1c90`. It adds raw outbound activation
events tied to the selected published revision, including a nullable
`aggregated_at` marker, plus durable daily aggregate dimensions keyed by
competition, target type, source surface, and anonymous/authenticated actor
kind. The periodic service serializes PostgreSQL workers with a transaction
advisory lock, marks newly counted rows in the same transaction, and deletes
only rows older than the exact `now - 90 days` event-time boundary.
Neither table stores a user, session, or device identifier. The recorded
`legacy_create_all` path remains unchanged. Downgrading drops both analytics
tables and their retained counts, so export any required metrics before a
shared-database rollback.

`seed-e2e --reset` rebuilds only the isolated browser-test database. It is not a
reset, migration, or recovery path for a development, shared, or production
database.
